//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: cannot be compared with `==`
//
// Equality is meant to be structural on every type, and is on primitives, `str`,
// records, tuples, lists and unions. Four shapes the backend cannot compare are
// refused rather than answered wrongly — before this, `Map == Map` returned false
// for equal maps (it compared two addresses) and a closure `==` reached the C
// compiler, which rejected it with a message naming a generated temp file.
//
// A closure is permanent: there is no structural answer. `Map`, a self-referencing
// record and a `List` behind `null` are gaps — each is an opaque pointer today. Note
// `P | null`, `str | null` and `i64 | null` are fine, since they carry a tag.

use std::io;
use std::collections::map;

fn main() {
    let a = map::set(map::new(), "k", 1);
    let b = map::set(map::new(), "k", 1);
    io::println("#{a == b}");
}
